{"key":"processedPost-11878377","value":{"id":11878377,"first":11877656,"last":11879824,"when":1264185912,"utime":"01/22/10 08:45 PM","content":"<blockquote>Quote:<br /> I feel if i misted enough to get that up closer to 100% it would over-saturate my casing... </blockquote><br />This is a commonly misunderstood part of fruiting, so don't feel frustrated-you're not alone.&nbsp; <br />If you're giving the correct amount of fresh air exchange, your substrate/casing layer WILL dry out, even at 99% humidity.&nbsp; You want your perlite or other humidification system to provide the humidity, and then you mist the substrate to replace moisture lost to evaporation due to the influx of fresh air.&nbsp; If your casing layer is too dry, you mist.&nbsp; Generally, several mistings per day are superior to one saturation per day.&nbsp; If your casing layer is too wet, the mushrooms will be very slow growing.&nbsp; The answer to the latter is increased air exchange to dry out the casing layer or substrate.&nbsp;  This evaporation of moisture from the growing medium is the number one pinning trigger.&nbsp; <br />That's why I also sometimes say the same thing as 'fresh air supply is the number one pinning trigger'.&nbsp; It's two ways of saying essentially the same thing, since fresh air will cause the evaporation you need for good pinning performance.<br />RR","title":"Re: question regarding fruiting"}}